Code Mystics handled the port, previously having developed the ''[[Atari Greatest Hits]]'' series for the [[Nintendo DS]], a similar collection of games updated for a modern system.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/01/22/atari-bringing-more-than-100-classics-to-steam-in-new-vault-collection.aspx | title = Atari Bringing More Than 100 Classics To Steam In New Vault Collection | work = [[Game Informer]] | date = January 22, 2016 | accessdate = January 22, 2016 | first = Jeff | last = Cork }}</ref> For ''Atari Vault'', they have worked to ensure that the games in this title would be considered the definitive modern versions, according to developer Matthew Labunka. They spent time to obtain fine details on the look and presentation, such as getting digital imagery of the arcade cabinet art to present alongside the game screen.<ref name="wired pax"/> The updated versions will be running the original games' [[ROM image]], wrapped into an emulator made in the [[Unity (game engine)|Unity 5]] game engine.<ref name="wired pax"/> In addition to original settings that were normally available to arcade players, the player can access options that were limited to the arcade cabinet operator, such as difficulty and length of a single play session.<ref name="wired pax"/> Art and related materials are also available for each game for the player to review.<ref name="wired pax"/>
Where possible, the games have been updated to include both local and online multiplayer, and games use Steam-based score leaderboards. The games have been tuned to use the [[Steam controller]], enabling precise controls for the games, particularly for games that used [[trackball]] input devices, like ''Centipede''.<ref name="wired announced">{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/2016/01/atari-vault-steam/ | title = Steam's Atari Vault Package Brings Back 100 Classic Games | first = Chris | last = Kohler | date = January 21, 2016 | accessdate = January 22, 2016 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] }}</ref> Code Mystics worked with [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] to fine-tune controller profiles for various games before release.<ref name="wired pax"/>
